[1] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Tue 1 Sep 2009
Source: A Tarde On Line [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.atarde.com.br/cidades/noticia.jsf?id=1221079>


The number of dengue cases recorded in Bahia between 1 Jan and 22 Aug
2009 has practically tripled, compared to the number of cases
registered during the same period in 2008. The [case] number is also
the highest since 1995, when dengue was considered for the 1st time
as epidemic and began to be counted in the state. The information was
provided by the state Secretariat of Health of Bahia (SESAB), which
recorded 103 788 [dengue] cases in the 1st 8 months of this year
[2009], compared to 34 125 [cases] registered during the same period
last year [2008], an increase of 204 percent.

According to SESAB, dengue is present in 402 of the 417
municipalities in Bahia, and the municipalities of Itabuna, Jequie,
Salvador, Feira de Santana, Irece, and Ilheus had 41 percent of the
cases. As for the most serious cases of the disease, SESAB recorded
1028 cases in 120 municipalities of Bahia, among which there were 60
confirmed [dengue] deaths.

The coordinator of Epidemiological Surveillance of the state of
Bahia, Jesuina Castro, attributed the increase in the number of cases
to the discontinuance of the policy of fighting dengue in some of the
municipalities in Bahia. She said this factor was fundamental to the
increase in the number of reported dengue cases this year [2009],
which would be a direct result of dismantling dengue control teams
after the change of government occurred in several municipalities in
2009. "It is extremely important that this does not happen in the
coming years when there is a change in government," she emphasizes.

The coordinator also said that we must be alert in the coming years
to a possible increase in the number of cases of the more severe
[type of] dengue. According to her, "even though the number of cases
decreases, there will be a large group, especially young people, who
had no contact with the form of the disease, which can facilitate the
transmission of the virus.

[Byline: Guilherme Lopes]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[If some of the municipal dengue control teams were, in fact,
eliminated, it illustrates the political difficulty of maintaining
preventive programs in the absence of an immediate health emergency.

