[3] Puerto Rico
Date: Fri 28 Aug 2009
Source: Ponte al Dia, Agencia EFE report [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.pontealdia.com/estados-unidos/piden-fumigar-puerto-rico-por-brote-de-dengue.html>


Senator Luis Daniel Muniz asked today [28 Aug 2009] of the newly
appointed secretary of the Department of Health, Lorenzo Gonzalez,
that he promote a massive fumigation plan for the entire island to
avoid the spread of dengue [virus transmission].

Muniz's demand comes after seeing the most recent Health report
relating to dengue, according to which in the past week there were a
total of 150 new suspected dengue cases, bringing the total of
possible carriers of the virus in Puerto Rico so far this year
[2009], to 3256. "We cannot focus only on the transmission of the A
(H1N1) [influenza] virus while the dengue cases continue to increase
in Puerto Rico," stated Muniz, who underscore also that fumigation is
a frequently used resource in many countries for prevention and
control of dengue. Muniz indicated that he hopes that the
implementation of this massive fumigation plan which, in his opinion
will avoid the deaths of people, "victims of a bad [disease] which
could have been avoided in time, will not "fall on deaf ears."

The press reported today [28 Aug 2009] the presumed [dengue] death of
a 9-year-old child, a student in the Cidra locale -- in the center of
the island -- although the data has not been confirmed yet by the
Health Department.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) of Atlanta, USA,
confirmed this past April [2009] the 1st death attributed to dengue
in Puerto Rico so far this year [2009], an 8-year-old girl in the
Caguas area, in the center of the Island.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[Although fumigation (fogging) with insecticides is a dramatic and
visible approach often favored when authorities are under public
pressure to "do something," the reduction of dengue vector mosquitoes
is temporary and less effective over the long-term than elimination
of water catchments in and around houses and other buildings that
serve as breeding sites of _Aedes_ mosquitoes.

Maps of Puerto Rico can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/puertorico.jpg>
and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00L*>. - Mod.TY]

